   <h1>Re: [T2] head temperature sensor</h1>
   <b>"Charles Watson" <sbcwat(-at-)hotmail.com></b><br/>
   <i>2002-03-23 23:47:59+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Sorry Matt

Its WD40 not WD9 (Just a elder moment).  I haven't used WD40 this way so 
can't recommend it. Propane works but both are a little scary.

Chuck

>From: "MATT GUERWITZ" 
>To: sbcwat(-at-)hotmail.com, type2(-at-)type2.com
>Subject: Re: [T2] head temperature sensor
>Date: Sat, 23 Mar 2002 23:00:57 +0000
>
>Hey Chuck,
>
>How are you? I just finished some work on my van. No success yet. This is
>what I did today.
>
>I installed a new head temperature sensor. I started the van and the same
>thing occured. It ran and then died shortly after. I next checked all 
>vacuum
>connections. Everything seemed to be fine. No cracked hoses and everything
>seems to be connected properly. To confirm this I completely turned in
>(clockwise) the hex screw on the Air Flow Measurement box as you suggested.
>I started the van and the same thing happened. Absolutely no change. I
>returned the screw to its original position (2 and one quarter turns out)
>and tried the van again. Same thing happened. All battery connections are
>clean.
>
>So what do you think? I don't know what to try next. Any advice?
>
>Thanks,
>
>Matt
>
>
>----Original Message Follows----
>From: "Charles Watson" 
>To: bretty(-at-)hotmail.com
>Subject: Re: [T2] head temperature sensor
>Date: Thu, 21 Mar 2002 17:15:29 -0800
>
>Matt
>I think that you have a major leak. Low level leaks would have to be
>numerous to cause such a condition on their own. I have had ground strap
>(battery to chassis) that caused all sort of weird symptoms. Just last 
>month
>a rusty strap caused starting problems. As I wiggled it it would go too a
>few ohms. A big ugly NAPA strap fixed that problem. A poor strap from the
>tyranny to chassis can cause the clutch cable to fail I am told. Seems
>conduction through the cable causes metal migration problems.
>
>Its hard to work in the cold.  Hunting for vacuum leaks has been a way of
>life for me and my 77.  I have to believe leaks are problematic in the 
>older
>FI models.
>
>You can adjust the Air Fuel Mix with the hex screw on top of the Air Flow
>Measurement box. Turn it clock wise until it hits bottom (count the turns).
>This is as rich a it can go. Hook up the sensor and see if it will run. 
>This
>mixture adjust inter acts with the idle adjust screw so the idle will most
>likely be off. But if this lets it run with sensor hooked up it points to a
>vacuum leak.
>
>In this case go to the Type2 search engine and type Vacuum leak for a 
>wealth
>of info.
>
>Good luck and let me know what you find.
>Chuck
>
>>From: "MATT GUERWITZ" 
>>To: sbcwat(-at-)hotmail.com
>>Subject: Re: [T2] head temperature sensor
>>Date: Fri, 22 Mar 2002 00:35:20 +0000
>>
>>Chuck,
>>
>>Last fall I was driving and the bus just died out. It didn't sputter or 
>>run
>>rough it just stop running. I pulled over took a look at the engine and
>>seen nothing. It immediately started again and off I went. This continued
>>happening. Not at an exact interval but consistently happening. It was
>>usually around 10 or 15 minutes of driving. It was at the end of the year
>>so I only drove a few times before I stored it for winter.
>>
>>I just took it out of storage and started it up and voila the new problem
>>has come up. It starts, runs at high rpm(around 2000), and then dies after
>>a minute. Everybody has been saying battery connections, vacuum tubes, or
>>head temperature sensor.
>>
>>I have cleaned all battery connections but have yet to check the ground
>>strap as someone mentioned. I have tested the sensor as I mentioned before
>>and from what you were saying it seems to be working. I have not started 
>>to
>>look for vacuum leaks but I do know that there is a big vacuum hose that
>>has a loose fit. It's the one that goes to the deaccellerator valve I
>>believe. It's connected but should be clamped. Would a loose fitting hose
>>cause such a problem?
>>
>>It has been snowing up here for the last week so not the most pleasent
>>weather to work in. Anyway I would like to get it running and tune it up
>>for spring.
>>
>>Thanks alot for your help,
>>
>>Matt
>>
>>
>>----Original Message Follows----
>>From: "Charles Watson" 
>>To: bretty(-at-)hotmail.com
>>Subject: Re: [T2] head temperature sensor
>>Date: Thu, 21 Mar 2002 11:46:54 -0800
>>
>>Matt
>>You are not wrong the colder the temp the higher the resistance and the
>>richer the fuel/air mix. What happened to start this problem off?
>>
>>Chuck
>>
>>To: sbcwat(-at-)hotmail.com
>>>Subject: Re: [T2] head temperature sensor
>>>Date: Thu, 21 Mar 2002 18:33:20 +0000
>>>
>>>Thanks Chuck,
>>>
>>>I live in Ottawa, ON, Canada and it was about 0 degrees celcius yesterday
>>>when I did the testing. Perhaps the cold temp is responsible for the high
>>>resistance before start up. I always thought it was the opposite though.
>>>That resistance decreased as temperature increased. Am I wrong? Anyway I
>>>will check all the vacuum hoses and get back to you with what I find.
>>>
>>>Matt
>>
